# Workspace CLAUDE.md — Example

This file is a **template** for a multi-company workspace directory (e.g.
`~/projects/`). Replace `<COMPANY_A>`, `<COMPANY_B>`, `<COMPANY_C>` with your own
organizations.

## Workspace overview

`~/projects/` is the **top-level workspace** for multiple companies and personal
projects. It is **not** a single git repo — each subdirectory is an independent project
or monorepo with its own git history, tooling, and `CLAUDE.md`.

**Always `cd` into the specific project directory and read its `CLAUDE.md` before doing
any work.**

---

## Directory map

| Directory | Belongs to | Description |
|-----------|-----------|-------------|
| `<company-a>/` | Company A | Primary monorepo — see its `CLAUDE.md` for full project list |
| `<company-b>/` | Company B | Company B projects |
| `<company-c>/` | Company C | Company C projects |
| `personal/` | Personal | Your personal tools |
| `Tools/` | Cross-company | MCP configs, scripts, persistent memory |

---

## MCP / integration tool selection

External service integrations should be **scoped per company**. Each company has its
own integration account. Always use the correct company's MCP server or CLI account.

For [Composio](https://composio.dev/), declare one MCP server per company in
`~/.claude.json`, using a per-company Tool Router session scoped to the correct user
and toolkits.

**Anti-patterns:**

- Do not cross-wire company credentials (e.g. Company A's API key in Company B's
  config)
- Do not use Claude.ai's built-in integrations alongside Composio — pick one
  integration layer
- Treat the workspace `.env` as the single source of truth for org-scoped credentials;
  prefix variables by org (`<COMPANY_A>_API_KEY`, etc.). Never commit it.

---

## Per-company server / infrastructure pattern

Each company runs on its own dedicated cloud instance. They are fully separate hosts
with separate cloud accounts, agent installs, configs, services, and credentials.
Never assume "the server" — always specify which one.

| Company | Instance | SSH alias | Region |
|---------|----------|-----------|--------|
| Company A | `<company-a>-main` | `<company-a>-server` | (region) |
| Company B | `<company-b>-main` | `<company-b>-server` | (region) |
| Company C | `<company-c>-main` | `<company-c>-server` | (region) |

Each company also runs its **own independent overlay network** (e.g. Tailscale). They
do not share the network and must not depend on each other.

### Webhook / trigger architecture

Automations that react to external events should be **webhook-triggered, not
cron-polled**. Each server runs a webhook receiver exposed via a public tunnel (e.g.
Tailscale Funnel or DuckDNS + nginx + Let's Encrypt), plus a Pub/Sub pull daemon for
Google services.

**Anti-patterns:**

- Do not re-introduce polling crons for events that can fire as webhooks (Gmail,
  Calendar, Slack, GitHub repo events, etc.)
- Do not use third-party trigger services that poll on a 2-minute interval — that is no
  better than cron

**What stays as cron (genuinely time-based):** daily reports, weekly digests, health
checks, scheduled posts.

---

## Universal architecture pattern

All projects follow **Domain-Driven Design**:

- Business / domain logic lives in `pipeline/`, `domains/`, or `services/`
- External API wrappers are infrastructure adapters — external types must not leak
  into domain logic
- API routes / entry points are thin controllers (validate → call service → return)
- No business logic in delivery mechanisms (MCP tools, Express routes, Next.js API
  routes, cron wrappers)

### Stack quick reference

| Pattern | Stack | Dev command |
|---------|-------|-------------|
| Python automation | Python 3.10+ / venv | `source venv/bin/activate && python -m pipeline.orchestrator` |
| Node MCP server | Node.js / TypeScript | `npm install && npm run dev` |
| Next.js + Bun | Next.js / Bun | `bun install && bun run dev` |
| Next.js + npm | Next.js / npm | `npm install && npm run dev` |
| React + Express | Vite + Express | `npm run install:all` then run client and server separately |

---

## Git workflow (all projects)

**Never commit directly to `main`.** Branch naming:

| Pattern | Use for |
|---------|---------|
| `feat/fe-<name>` | Frontend features |
| `feat/be-<name>` | Backend features |
| `bug-fix/<name>` | Bug fixes |
| `hot-fix/<name>` | Production hotfixes |

Commit format (Conventional Commits):

```
type(scope): short description (max 72 chars)

Explanation of what changed and why.
```

Allowed types: `feat` `fix` `chore` `docs` `refactor` `test` `ci` `perf` `style`
`build`

`--no-verify` is prohibited.

### Linear ↔ PR linking convention

If your project tracker (Linear, Jira, etc.) supports auto-linking from PR body magic
words, prefer that over branch-name auto-linking. Branch-name conventions (`feat/`,
`bug-fix/`) typically conflict with project-tracker branch patterns
(`username/TEAM-123-...`).

**The rule for every PR:**

1. If the work corresponds to an existing tracker issue, include exactly one line in
   the PR body:
   ```
   Closes <TEAM>-123
   ```
2. If the issue should stay open after merge, use `Refs <TEAM>-123` instead of
   `Closes`.
3. If there is no tracker issue, omit the line entirely. **Do not fabricate IDs.**
4. To find the right ID: ask, grep the branch's commit messages, or query the tracker
   API.

**Anti-patterns:**

- Do not put the tracker ID in the branch name — your pre-push hook will reject it
- Do not skip the magic word — it is the only auto-link mechanism that works in this
  setup
- Do not use tracker URLs in the body as a substitute — they typically do not trigger
  auto-attach

---

## Parallel agent dispatch (optional)

If you use a parallel-agent orchestrator (e.g.
[legion / HolyClaude](https://github.com/holyclaude/holyclaude-cloud)), drop a config
file (`legion.toml` or equivalent) at the workspace root as a template, and use a
`chpwd` hook in your shell rc to auto-seed it into any new git repo under the
workspace.

For high-stakes client repos, add a **lockdown rule** that skips auto-seed and disables
auto-merge automation. The cost of a wrong AI-driven change on a high-stakes client
(reputational + commercial) far outweighs time saved by automation.

---

## Email / message formatting rules

When drafting emails or messages on your behalf, Claude should follow these rules:

- **Plain text only** — no Markdown, no asterisks, no headers, no bullets with symbols
- Paragraphs separated by a single blank line
- Lists use line breaks only (no hyphens, numbers, or bullet characters)
- Avoid em dashes — use commas, periods, or parentheses
- Friendly, human tone — not cringe, not mechanical
- Output must be copy-paste ready without any cleanup
- Always include a clear CTA or next step

Run a mental sanity pass before returning any email: no Markdown artifacts, clear
paragraph breaks, skimmable, human-sounding.
